{"parse":{"title":"Children of the plantation","pageid":448905,"revid":859862774,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>In the context of <a href=\"/wiki/Slavery_in_the_colonial_United_States\" title=\"Slavery in the colonial United States\">slavery in the colonial United States</a>, the expression <b>\"children of the plantation\"</b> was a <a href=\"/wiki/Euphemism\" title=\"Euphemism\">euphemism</a> used to identify the offspring of black female <a href=\"/wiki/Plantation_slaves\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Plantation slaves\">plantation slaves</a> by white men, usually the owner or one of his sons or the <a href=\"/wiki/Plantations_in_the_American_South#Overseer\" title=\"Plantations in the American South\">plantation overseer</a>. \n</p><p>Such children, who were born into slavery (a legal doctrine known as <i><a href=\"/wiki/Partus_sequitur_ventrem\" title=\"Partus sequitur ventrem\">partus sequitur ventrem</a></i>), were seldom acknowledged by their white fathers.<sup class=\"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">&#91;<i><a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed\" title=\"Wikipedia:Citation needed\"><span title=\"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (February 2008)\">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup> These children were classified as <a href=\"/wiki/Mulatto#Antebellum_era\" title=\"Mulatto\">mulatto</a>, a historic term for a <a href=\"/wiki/Multiracial\" title=\"Multiracial\">multiracial</a> person. The <a href=\"/wiki/One_drop_rule\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"One drop rule\">one drop rule</a> meant that they could never be part of white society.\n</p><p>One famous example is the decades-long relationship between President <a href=\"/wiki/Thomas_Jefferson\" title=\"Thomas Jefferson\">Thomas Jefferson</a> and his slave (and possible half-sister of his wife) <a href=\"/wiki/Sally_Hemings\" title=\"Sally Hemings\">Sally Hemings</a>. The <a href=\"/wiki/Jefferson%E2%80%93Hemings_controversy\" title=\"Jefferson\u2013Hemings controversy\">Jefferson\u2013Hemings controversy</a>, now resolved by DNA testing, shows that all her children were his. In the <a href=\"/wiki/Antebellum_period\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Antebellum period\">antebellum period</a>, hers would have been called a \"shadow family\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p><a href=\"/wiki/Alex_Haley\" title=\"Alex Haley\">Alex Haley</a>'s <i><a href=\"/wiki/Queen:_The_Story_of_an_American_Family\" title=\"Queen: The Story of an American Family\">Queen: The Story of an American Family</a></i> (1993) is a <a href=\"/wiki/Historical_novel\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Historical novel\">historical novel</a>, later a movie, that brought knowledge of the \"children of the plantation\" to public attention.\n</p><p>After the Civil War and emancipation, similar relationships continued. For example, <a href=\"/wiki/Strom_Thurmond\" title=\"Strom Thurmond\">Strom Thurmond</a>, who as a senator pursued segregationist policies, fathered a child when he was a young man, forcing himself on his family's 15 year old maid. This child, <a href=\"/wiki/Essie_Mae_Washington-Williams\" title=\"Essie Mae Washington-Williams\">Essie Mae Washington-Williams</a>, did not reveal the story until he died, when she was 78. Her parentage had been an open secret in the black community, but came as a surprise to the late senator's colleagues.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Children_of_the_plantation&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Slave_breeding_in_the_United_States\" title=\"Slave breeding in the United States\">Slave breeding in the United States</a></li>\n<li><i><a href=\"/wiki/Pla%C3%A7age\" title=\"Pla\u00e7age\">Pla\u00e7age</a></i></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Sexual_slavery\" title=\"Sexual slavery\">Sexual slavery</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Children_of_the_plantation&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Lewis, Jan. <i>Sally Hemings &amp; Thomas Jefferson: History, Memory, and Civic Culture</i>. p.&#160;14.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Sally+Hemings+%26+Thomas+Jefferson%3A+History%2C+Memory%2C+and+Civic+Culture&amp;rft.pages=14&amp;rft.aulast=Lewis&amp;rft.aufirst=Jan&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AChildren+of+the+plantation\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external autonumber\" href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/2003/12/18/us/final-word-my-father-s-name-was-james-strom-thurmond.html\">[1]</a></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw2230\nCached time: 20180916195537\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.076 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.103 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 252/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand inc